TEXT 776 184 Left 2 !.MODEL myBJT npn(IS=2.05e-14 BF=100 BR=1.88)
TEXT 72 640 Left 2 ;This is an example of a Joule Thief circuit.\nThe current BJT model is based on a simplified definition, using the Ebers-Moll model, consistent with the formulas used in the calculation files.\nYou can replace the BJT model with the SPICE model included with LTSPICE or downloaded from the manufacturer's website.\nHowever, note that they are typically based on the Modified Gummel-Poon model. \nWhen comparing simulation results with theoretical calculations, you can extract Is and BR from the model, but you will need to experimentally calibrate BF (for theory) to reflect the high injection effect.\nThe Joule Thief circuit is not limited to the BJT model. In fact, you can also use an NMOS model (while removing Rb), which offers higher power conversion efficiency.
TEXT 72 840 Left 2 ;The parameters of the coupling inductor are from the MSD1278H. You can replace them as needed.\nIt is recommended to use a Schottky diode to reduce voltage drop.\nThe main function of the output capacitor is to reduce ripple. A larger value is recommended (common models range from 10uF to 22uF).
TEXT 1256 280 Left 2 ;If you find it helpful, please cite our paper:\n \nS. Su and S. Aunet, "Self-Oscillating Joule Thief Converters for MEMS Electromagnetic Energy Harvesting: Analytical Modeling and Experimental Validation," in IEEE Transactions on Industrial Electronics, doi: 10.1109/TIE.2026.3663767.\n \nhttps://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/11434838
TEXT 1048 144 Left 2 ;You can replace myBJT with other BJT, or NMOS (remove Rb too)
TEXT 936 72 Left 2 !.options reltol=1e-3
